04499nam a22006615i 9781400880959DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984650508  a97814008809597 a10.1515/97814008809592doi  a(DE-B1597)468049  a(OCoLC)945735900  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0370002bisacsh1 aBashford, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Worlds of Thomas Robert Malthus :bRereading the Principle of Population /cJoyce E. Chaplin, Alison Bashford. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b12 halftones. 2 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Population and the New World -- tChapter 1. Population, Empire, and America -- tChapter 2. Writing the Essay -- tPart II: New Worlds in the Essay, c. 1803 -- tChapter 3. New Holland -- tChapter 4. The Americas -- tChapter 5. The South Sea -- tPart III: Malthus and the New World, 1803–1834 -- tChapter 6. Slavery and Abolition -- tChapter 7. Colonization and Emigration -- tChapter 8. The Essay in New Worlds -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe New Worlds of Thomas Robert Malthus is a sweeping global and intellectual history that radically recasts our understanding of Malthus's Essay on the Principle of Population, the most famous book on population ever written or ever likely to be. Malthus's Essay is also persistently misunderstood. First published anonymously in 1798, the Essay systematically argues that population growth tends to outpace its means of subsistence unless kept in check by factors such as disease, famine, or war, or else by lowering the birth rate through such means as sexual abstinence.Challenging the widely held notion that Malthus's Essay was a product of the British and European context in which it was written, Alison Bashford and Joyce Chaplin demonstrate that it was the new world, as well as the old, that fundamentally shaped Malthus's ideas. They explore what the Atlantic and Pacific new worlds—from the Americas and the Caribbean to New Zealand and Tahiti—meant to Malthus, and how he treated them in his Essay. Bashford and Chaplin reveal how Malthus, long vilified as the scourge of the English poor, drew from his principle of population to conclude that the extermination of native populations by European settlers was unjust.Elegantly written and forcefully argued, The New Worlds of Thomas Robert Malthus relocates Malthus's Essay from the British economic and social context that has dominated its reputation to the colonial and global history that inspired its genesis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMalthusianism. 0aPopulation. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aChaplin, Joyce E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140088095940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400880959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400880959.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK